Abstract

This paper argues that Dario Amodei and similarly positioned frontier AI executives have engaged in a form of defamation by implication against ordinary people, independent researchers, open-source developers, open-weight model builders, and the general public.

The allegation is not merely that Amodei has warned about AI risk. The allegation is that he repeatedly frames broad access to powerful AI as a danger arising from ordinary people, “non-state actors,” “malicious but otherwise average people,” open-source models, and uncontrolled deployment, while simultaneously presenting Anthropic and comparable closed laboratories as the responsible custodians of the same technology.

That structure does reputational work. It tells governments, journalists, regulators, and the public that people outside frontier labs are presumptively unsafe. It implies that people Amodei has never met, cannot assess, and has no mandate to judge are dangerous custodians of technology, while his own company is treated as safer by institutional self-description.

This paper calls that conduct character defamation by safety positioning.

