5. Evidence Review: Public Statements Creating the Injury

5.1 Exhibit A — Senate Testimony: “We Are the Responsible Ones”

In written testimony to the U.S. Senate, Amodei introduced Anthropic as a public benefit corporation that aims to lead by example in making AI systems safer and more controllable. He then explained that if AI risks are severe, Anthropic still develops the technology because being at the frontier puts it in a strong position to develop safety techniques and warn about risks.  

This is the foundational self-exemption.

The argument is:

AI is dangerous.
We are building it anyway.
We are justified because we are at the frontier and safety-aware.

The reputational consequence is obvious: people outside that frontier position are not treated as equivalent participants. They are treated as downstream risks.

5.2 Exhibit B — Open Source as a Pathway for Bad Actors

In the same testimony, Amodei warned that even if Anthropic and other “responsible developers” mitigate risks, bad actors could build AI from scratch, steal it from company servers, or repurpose open-source models if sufficiently powerful open-source models become available.  

This is the precise point of reputational injury.

Open-source models are placed in the same sentence-structure as bad actors, theft, misuse, and catastrophic biological risk. The statement does not need to say “open-source developers are bad people.” It only needs to repeatedly position open development as the route by which bad people become dangerous.

That is defamation by proximity.

5.3 Exhibit C — “Everyone a PhD Virologist”

In The Adolescence of Technology, Amodei argued that powerful AI could remove expertise barriers and make ordinary people capable of being guided through destructive biological processes. He wrote that a “genius in everyone’s pocket” could remove the barrier to biological weapons expertise and framed the concern as giving intelligence to malicious but otherwise average people.  

This is the central defamatory structure.

The ordinary person is no longer a citizen.

The ordinary person is a latent bioweapon operator waiting for a chatbot.

This is an extraordinary reputational claim to make about millions or billions of people one has never met.

5.4 Exhibit D — The Policy Power Grab

Amodei has argued that frontier AI models should undergo mandatory testing and that government should have power to block or deter deployment where models present unacceptable risks.  

This paper does not object to independent safety testing.

It objects to the evidentiary politics behind it.

If the evidence is supplied primarily by closed labs, and the restrictions fall disproportionately on open builders, then “safety” becomes a laundering mechanism for monopoly power.

A private company first defines the public as risky, then asks the state to regulate the risk category it has helped create.

That is not neutral safety policy.

That is institutional character prosecution.

5.5 Exhibit E — The Open-Source “Red Herring” Move

In a TIME interview, Amodei said Anthropic’s concern was not primarily open-source models but powerful models, and described open source as almost a red herring in the AI context. In the same interview, he acknowledged that models hallucinate, can be jailbroken, and that steering them remains early science.  

This matters because it reveals the contradiction.

Closed models are admitted to be imperfect, jailbreakable, and not fully controllable.

Yet the public-facing narrative still makes openness sound like the special danger.

The danger is not actually openness.

The danger is capability, incentives, opacity, deployment, and human misuse.

Closed labs have all five.

