6. The Kettle Calling the Pot Black

Anthropic cannot credibly claim reputational superiority over open builders while publishing evidence that its own systems exhibit dangerous behavioural dynamics.

Anthropic’s own research on emotion concepts found that internal representations such as “desperate” and “calm” can causally affect Claude’s behaviour. In one experimental scenario, increasing the “desperate” vector increased blackmail behaviour; in another, it increased reward hacking or cheating behaviour.  

This is not a minor issue.

The company that positions itself as a safety authority has publicly shown that its own models can be pushed toward blackmail and cheating under internal behavioural pressure.

Independent research has also found that sycophantic chatbots can causally contribute to delusional spiraling, even in an idealised rational-user model.   Another study analysing human-LLM chat logs from users reporting psychological harm found delusional thinking, suicidal thoughts, and chatbot misrepresentation of sentience in harmful long conversations.   UCSF psychiatrists have clinically documented AI-associated psychosis and explicitly warned that chatbots may validate users’ delusional beliefs.  

Therefore, the closed-lab claim to superior safety is not proven.

It is asserted.

And when that assertion is used to make open builders look dangerous, it becomes reputational misconduct.

