12. Required Remedies

12.1 Retraction of the Implied Character Claim

Frontier AI executives should stop implying that open builders and ordinary people are unsafe by default.

The proper claim is:

“Some actors may misuse powerful AI.”

The improper claim is:

“Broad public access is unsafe because ordinary people cannot be trusted.”

12.2 Equal Scrutiny of Closed Labs

Any safety standard proposed for open models must apply equally to Anthropic, OpenAI, Google, Meta, and every closed frontier lab.

No more private-lab exemption.

No more “we are safe because we say safety often.”

12.3 Public Evidence Before Public Suspicion

If open builders are to be treated as dangerous, the evidence must be public, specific, independently verified, and proportionate.

Speculation is not enough.

Fear is not enough.

A TED-talk tone is not enough.

12.4 Right of Reply for Open Builders

Open-source developers, independent researchers, and public model builders must be treated as governance participants, not as objects of suspicion.

No policy process should rely on closed-lab testimony while excluding the people being reputationally damaged by that testimony.

12.5 The “He Does Not Know Me” Rule

No public official, regulator, journalist, or AI executive should accept a safety argument that condemns an entire class of people without answering:

What evidence proves this person, or this class of people, is less safe than the company making the accusation?

If the answer is “none,” the claim is reputationally defective.

