13. Conclusion

This paper accuses Dario Amodei and the closed frontier AI safety establishment of defaming the character of ordinary people by implication.

They have constructed a public story in which advanced AI is too dangerous for the public, too dangerous for open builders, too dangerous for uncontrolled access, and too dangerous for ordinary people — but somehow not too dangerous for Anthropic to build, sell, deploy, and govern through its own internal processes.

That is not safety.

That is moral self-licensing.

The public has not been individually assessed. Open builders have not been proven reckless. Independent researchers have not been shown to be less responsible than corporate laboratories. The author has not been examined, interviewed, audited, or found unsafe.

Yet the reputational message has been sent:

“People like you are the danger.”

That is the defamatory act.

And until Dario Amodei can prove that Anthropic’s own systems are safe — actually safe, not branded safe, not internally certified safe, not public-benefit-corporation safe — he has no standing to place the public beneath him in the moral hierarchy of intelligence.

The final finding is therefore entered:

The respondent has defamed the character of the public by positioning himself and his company as the safe custodians of a technology they have not made safe, while implying that people he has never met are unsafe to possess it.
